  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks against money laundering. The primary international body that sets standards and promotes measures to combat money laundering is the Financial Action Task Force (FATF). The FATF is an intergovernmental organization established in 1989 by the G7 to develop policies to combat money laundering and, later, the financing of terrorism.\n\nThe FATF has issued a series of recommendations known as the FATF Recommendations, which are recognized as the international standard for combating money laundering and the financing of terrorism. These recommendations include measures that countries should implement to:\n\n1. Identify and assess the money laundering and terrorist financing risks they face.\n2. Implement the necessary legal and regulatory framework to address these risks, including criminalizing money laundering and enabling the confiscation of proceeds of crime.\n3. Establish a framework for customer due diligence and reporting of suspicious transactions.\n4. Ensure that financial institutions and other obligated entities maintain appropriate records and are subject to effective supervision and regulation.\n5. Facilitate international cooperation in investigations and prosecutions of money laundering and related crimes.\n\nCountries that are members of the FATF or are part of FATF-style regional bodies (FSRBs) are expected to implement these recommendations into their national legal systems. The FATF also conducts mutual evaluations of its members to assess their compliance with the recommendations and to identify areas for improvement.\n\nIn addition to the FATF, other international bodies such as the United Nations, through conventions like the United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) and the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000), also play a role in the international fight against money laundering. These conventions require signatory countries to criminalize money laundering and take measures to detect, prevent, and prosecute such activities.\n\nIt's important to note that while there are international standards and conventions, the implementation and enforcement of anti-money laundering (AML) laws are the responsibility of individual countries. The effectiveness of these laws can vary significantly from one jurisdiction to another due to differences in legal systems, regulatory frameworks, and enforcement capabilities.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
